- Exported target user's HKCU registry hive using reg export

- Injected a malicious Run key into the exported .reg file

- Used Offline Registry API (offreg.dll) to convert .reg 
  into a binary hive file named NTUSER.MAN

- Placed NTUSER.MAN in target user's %USERPROFILE% directory

- Windows loaded the malicious hive at next login and 
  executed the attacker's payload

- No live registry API calls were made — CrowdStrike did 
  not alert on the registry modification

- Raised a case with CrowdStrike on the offreg.dll 
  detection gap

- Created a Custom IOA rule to detect NTUSER.MAN 
  creation in user profile directories as a 
  compensating control
